    <h2>
      CHAPTER VI&mdash;AN ATTACK ON THE HIGH SEAS
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">M</span>r. manager
      frowningshield took up the copy of the <i>Sphere</i> in his hand, and
      gazed with troubled brow at this conclusive evidence of the date.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; he said at last, &ldquo;he was in England a week later than we were, and
      must have come direct to this spot, passing us somewhere on the way;
      during the night, probably.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain was now standing up, his fists clenched.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you propose to do?&rdquo; inquired the manager.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I should like to know first whether we are here as his guests or his
      prisoners. We were fools to have accepted his invitation without giving
      ourselves time to think and consult.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But, hang it all, captain, he came on us so unexpectedly that there was
      no time to plan, or even to suspect. He seemed to speak so honestly and
      straightforwardly, and was so ready with his explanation that even up to a
      moment ago I believed he was but a blameless tourist, with, eccentric
      tastes, and the money to indulge them; a craze for big game shooting, like
      so many of them toffs have, and, of course, that kind of a man is mouching
      all over the world. You meet them everywhere: South America, Africa, Asia.
      Of course he&rsquo;s got us aboard here, and could steam away past your ship,
      and my settlement, with us two flung down the hold, and helpless, just as
      I put away that Scotch engineer on the <i>Rajah</i> at Southampton. By
      Jove, I shouldn&rsquo;t wonder a bit but that&rsquo;s what&rsquo;s in his mind: taking a
      leaf out of my own book. We would have no chance of self-defense with so
      many men on board, and our steam launch could not keep within sight of him
      if this boat has turbine engines. The mines are exploded, and the way is
      clear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t you think your men would give her a shot as she went by?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not unless I was there to command them. I&rsquo;ve left nobody in authority. I
      wonder what he&rsquo;s doing so long down below? If we are his guests, he should
      be here to entertain us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is probably giving his orders,&rdquo; said the captain gloomily. &ldquo;We are
      trapped, my boy. He wouldn&rsquo;t leave us this long to consult together unless
      he was sure of us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why hasn&rsquo;t your mate come up from the launch?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I told him to stay there until I called him. You see, I had my doubts of
      this man from the first. If he attempts to lay hands on us, I&rsquo;ll shout to
      the mate to cut for it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What good could that do?&rdquo; protested the manager. &ldquo;The motor boat can
      overtake our launch even if she were half way to camp.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, here he comes,&rdquo; said the captain, as Stran-leigh, debonair and
      smiling, appeared at the head of the companion way. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll settle the
      question whether we are prisoners or not within two seconds.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I hope you&rsquo;ll excuse me,&rdquo; began Stranleigh, coming forward, &ldquo;but you are
      the first guests I have had the pleasure of receiving aboard since I left
      England, and I wish my to do his best, so I took the liberty of giving
      special orders for our lunch, and the gong will ring, they tell me, in
      about a quarter of an hour.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am very sorry, Mr. Stranleigh,&rdquo; replied the captain, &ldquo;but I am a little
      anxious about my ship, so I have told my mate to remain in our launch, and
      I must ask you to excuse me. I cannot remain to lunch.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dear me, I&rsquo;m sorry,&rdquo; said Stranleigh. &ldquo;Why is that? What harm can come to
      your steamer?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I&rsquo;ve seen those logs piled up still very close to the brink of the
      river, and I fear if they tumbled down also, coming end on upon us, they
      might do the <i>Rajah</i> some damage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My men tell me,&rdquo; Stranleigh reassured him, &ldquo;that there&rsquo;s no further
      danger of more logs getting into the river. Still, they are such fools
      that they may possibly be mistaken, and I quite share and sympathize with
      your anxiety. By the way, did any of the other logs damage your boat?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That I don&rsquo;t know yet. Some of them certainly struck her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then, captain, you must let me pay for whatever damage has been done;
      yes, and overpay, because, after all, I am the man responsible. Of course,
      you see, when we came up the river, there was no ship there, and no sign
      of any settlement. Still, that does not excuse my not having kept a better
      outlook. If the timber struck the steamer, is it likely the damage will be
      serious?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That, of course, I cannot tell without examination,&rdquo; replied the master
      of the <i>Rajah</i>.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, captain, we come of a sporting race. I&rsquo;ll give you a hundred pounds
      here in gold, win or lose. If the damage is a thousand pounds, then you&rsquo;ve
      lost. If there&rsquo;s no damage at all, you&rsquo;ve won a hundred pounds. Come,
      captain, what do you say?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If no damage has been done, Mr. Stranleigh, I don&rsquo;t want any money from
      you. Even if the steamer is hurt, I am not sure I should have a valid
      claim against you. After all, the affair was an accident.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you satisfied to give me a quit claim for a hundred pounds, cash
      down?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll be quite satisfied if you excuse me from attending luncheon, and
      allow me to go back to my ship.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, certainly, but I&rsquo;d like you to take the money. Can&rsquo;t you send the
      mate, and order him to come back and report to you? It&rsquo;s a pity to miss a
      meal, you know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;d feel safer if I went myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I know exactly how anxious you must feel, and in your place I should
      do the same. Very well, captain, the only point between us is the hundred
      pounds or not. To tell the truth, I shall not object to pay full
      compensation to your owners for what I have done. I imagine, however, so
      stanch a ship as yours has come to no harm. She lies bow upstream, and the
      current is not so strong down there as it is up here. The timber, I think,
      if it struck at all, would glance off, carrying away nothing but a bit of
      paint; but if you must go, I shall insist on your taking the hundred
      pounds.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Take the money, captain,&rdquo; said the manager, looking up at him with a
      smile. It was evident that his fears had once more been overcome, but the
      captain was not so easily cajoled.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very well,&rdquo; he said, anxious to end the situation and learn whether he
      was to be let go or not.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And now, Mr. Frowningshield,&rdquo; continued Stranleigh, turning to the
      manager, &ldquo;let us settle all our financial affairs before lunch, so that we
      may enjoy our meal without the thought of commercialism at the hoard. You
      have seen the damage I have caused in your forest, thinking all the while
      it was my own property. Of course, if you were acting for yourself alone,
      I am certain I could drive a very easy bargain with you, but you are
      responsible for the care of these lands to the European syndicate you
      spoke of, and so, on its behalf, you must be just, rather than generous.
      At how much coin of the realm do you place my depredations? I know it
      would cost me a pretty penny if I committed so unforgivable a trespass in
      England.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How many trees did you cut down, Mr. Stranleigh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, Lord knows! Twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, sixty, or a hundred
      perhaps. That can easily be discovered. We&rsquo;ll send a man across in the
      motor boat to count the stumps.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, it isn&rsquo;t worth while. Would you be content to part with another
      hundred pounds?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Done; and you&rsquo;ve let me off cheaply, Mr. Frowningshield. Just pardon me a
      moment until I get the money,&rdquo; and once more he disappeared down below.
    </p>
    <p>
      But all this had not changed in the least the captain&rsquo;s apprehension.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He&rsquo;s gone to give the signal,&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, you know, captain, I&rsquo;ve a great regard for you, yet I cannot find
      it possible to distrust the faith of that young man. He may be a fool, but
      he&rsquo;s a gentleman. I don&rsquo;t believe he would invite three men to a feast,
      and then imprison them. Now, I&rsquo;m no fool, but then I&rsquo;m no gentleman,
      either, and I&rsquo;d do it in a minute, if I had an enemy in my power, yet I&rsquo;m
      sure he won&rsquo;t. You&rsquo;ll see him come up with the money, and you&rsquo;ll miss a
      mighty good feed by going off to the <i>Rajah</i>.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;m willing to miss the meal, if I once get aboard my ship. I&rsquo;ll turn her
      round, and make for the ocean within the hour. You stop here as long as
      you can; all afternoon, if possible, and give the <i>Rajah</i> a chance to
      get out of sight before this fellow follows.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But he can easily overtake you. Still, what could he do if he did? You
      surely don&rsquo;t expect him to seize your vessel?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know what I expect, but I am afraid of him. I think him quite
      capable of following me to sea, and capturing the <i>Rajah</i>.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nonsense, that would be rank piracy. That would be a hanging matter. It
      would do him no good to sink you, and what could he do with the <i>Rajah</i>
      once he had her? There are too many witnesses on board. He wouldn&rsquo;t dare
      to sail into any port in the world. But then there&rsquo;s not the slightest
      danger of that. He&rsquo;s no pirate. The days of piracy are past. He may be a
      fool, but he&rsquo;s not such a fool as to try a trick like that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you stop here and give me a chance to get away?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Willingly.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very well, if I once get out of sight there are ten chances to one he
      can&rsquo;t catch me before I&rsquo;m in the Tagus.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Stranleigh reappeared with some rolls of gold done up in paper, and these
      he divided equally between the captain and Frowningshield. The latter
      could not resist the temptation of asking a question.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been looking at this illustrated newspaper, and I notice its date is
      very recent. You must have made a quick voyage from England, Mr.
      Stranleigh.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      For a moment they had the young man on the hip, but he did not allow the
      knowledge of this to change the expression of his placid face. He took the
      journal in his hand, and looked at the date.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, they do these things quickly nowadays, but perhaps not so quickly as
      one unaccustomed to journalism would imagine. I believe that the
      illustrated weeklies are dated some time ahead, and I have been told they
      send forth their foreign editions as far in advance as possible. This,
      now, could have come from London, through by way of Paris to Lisbon, and
      reach that city probably several days before the date mentioned on the
      cover. I must ask the doctor where he bought this copy, whether at Lisbon
      or Teneriffe.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He flung the <i>Sphere</i> carelessly down on the table as if the matter,
      after all, was of no moment, and even Frowningshield, who was watching him
      like a detective of fiction, could distinguish no note of hesitation in
      his voice, nor catch any glance of annoyance from his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, Mr. Stranleigh,&rdquo; said the captain, who was not equally successful
      in keeping an inflection of anxiety from his words, &ldquo;I am very much
      obliged to you for your invitation, even though I cannot take advantage of
      it, so I shall bid you good-by.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, you&rsquo;re not away yet, captain,&rdquo; said Stranleigh, with a slight laugh,
      and the captain drew himself up with a little start of surprise.
      Stran-leigh walked to the head of the companion way, and said:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you be as quick as you can down there?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As his back turned on them, the captain grasped Frowningshield&rsquo;s wrist.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He&rsquo;s playing with me like a cat with a mouse,&rdquo; he whispered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nonsense,&rdquo; replied the other. &ldquo;Your nerves have gone wrong. He&rsquo;s as
      transparent as glass.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Stranleigh turned, followed this time by a steward carrying a hamper,
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t like to think of your losing your lunch, captain,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;so
      I&rsquo;ve had them put up a basketful for you and the mate on your way to the
      <i>Rajah</i>. There is in the hamper several bottles of champagne that I
      think will commend itself to you, or to any other judge of a good vintage,
      and there is also a box of cigars. If these weeds do not elicit the
      highest commendation I&rsquo;ll insist that you bestow on me a better box the
      next time we meet. So good-by, captain, and good luck to you. May you sail
      the high seas prosperously and safely. Here&rsquo;s hoping I shall meet you
      again when you are not in such a hurry.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Basket and hamper had been placed in the launch, and Stranleigh waved his
      hand at the captain and mate as their craft steamed out into the current
      and made for the mining camp.
    </p>
    <p>
      The gong sounded out at last.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, Mr. Frowningshield,&rdquo; said the young man, returning from the side,
      &ldquo;if you&rsquo;re as hungry as I am, you&rsquo;ll enjoy this meal. Come along.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The manager did enjoy the meal, and they lingered long over the consuming
      of it, coming up on deck after it was over to indulge in coffee, liquors,
      and cigars. The manager fell under the charm of the young man&rsquo;s
      conversation, and began to revise his first estimate that his host was a
      fool. He had drunk but sparingly of the generous wine, yet in the glow of
      contentment which it produced he laughed quietly to himself now and then
      at the unfounded fears of the captain, which had cause him to run away
      from so excellent a repast.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If this is a cigar from a similar box to the one you gave the captain,
      the old man is to be congratulated.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, it is. The captain, of course, will see civilization long before you
      do, and so can provide himself with any variety of the weed he fancies;
      but you, in this out-of-the-world place, are not so fortunate, therefore I
      must beg of you to accept six boxes in remembrance of the enjoyable time I
      have spent in your society.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, Mr. Stranleigh, I&rsquo;m awfully much obliged, and I may tell you at once
      I am not going to refuse. A man doesn&rsquo;t get a present like that every year
      of his life, worse luck.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then to make up the average, Mr. Frowning-shield, you must let me add a
      few cases of our champagne.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Really, you are most kind. I don&rsquo;t know how to thank you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t attempt it, I beg of you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A steward approached and presented Stranleigh with a sealed envelope,
      which, begging the pardon of his guest, he tore open, saying:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I give all my orders in writing, so that there can be no mistake, and I
      rarely receive verbal reports from any one.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A good idea,&rdquo; said Frowningshield.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, it prevents disputes afterwards.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He read to himself the penciled words of the telegrapher who had
      transcribed a wireless message from the hilltop.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The <i>Rajah</i> is turning round, and is evidently about to depart.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Stranleigh, with a pencil, wrote on the back of the letter the following
      dispatch to Mackeller.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Report once more if the <i>Rajah</i> actually sails; then take with you
      anything you don&rsquo;t want to leave, and come down to the water. The motor
      boat will be waiting for you. Come aboard at the prow, and get immediately
      out of sight in the forecastle, for sitting aft with me is the man who
      kicked you down into the hold, and I don&rsquo;t wish him to recognize you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Giving this to the waiting steward, Stranleigh resumed conversation with
      his guest, who showed no desire to depart. Shortly after came the second
      message: &ldquo;The Rajah has sailed. Send motor boat now.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Stranleigh folded up the sheet of paper, and handed it to the steward.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Give that to the captain,&rdquo; he said, and a few minutes later the purr of
      the motor boat was heard leaving the ship. The sound aroused
      Frowningshield.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you sending away the motor boat?&rdquo; he asked. &ldquo;As our steam launch has
      not returned, I fear I must depend on you for getting me down to the
      camp.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, that&rsquo;s all right,&rdquo; replied Stranleigh easily. &ldquo;The boat isn&rsquo;t going
      far; just to pick up two of my men who&rsquo;ve been prospecting in the hills.
      In fact, this is the end of my trespass, for there is little use in my
      gazing on a Promised Land that has been promised to somebody else. As for
      the motor boat, and getting to camp, I can take you there more comfortably
      than on that little craft. You see, there&rsquo;s nothing further to keep me
      here, as I have said, unless I can make terms with your syndicate, and
      that very likely would not suit my book, because cheapness of land was one
      of my objects in coming so far. If your syndicate expects to find valuable
      minerals on this property, they are not likely to sell any of their
      holdings to me at such a price as I should care to pay, so I think I shall
      cast off and away, but whether I shall go north or south will depend on
      circumstances when I get out to sea.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What, you are not going to sail to-night, are you?&rdquo; said Frowningshield,
      sitting up.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, there&rsquo;s no use in stopping here any longer. Do you happen to know
      any place along the coast which would be suitable as a colonizing place
      for Englishmen? I should like it to resemble this as much as possible:
      hills, a large flow of pure water, free from any fever swamps, and good
      soil.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, Mr. Stranleigh, this is the only portion of Africa I am acquainted
      with.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s very likely the captain of the <i>Rajah</i> may be able to give me
      some hints. He has probably knocked around the world a bit, and doubtless
      has kept his eyes open. I wish I had thought of asking him before he left
      whether or not he knows this coast. Besides, I would like to learn for
      certain if I have damaged his ship. It&rsquo;s a good thing she wasn&rsquo;t facing
      the other way, otherwise a log might have wrecked rudder or screw, or
      both.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am afraid,&rdquo; stammered Frowningshield, &ldquo;that you won&rsquo;t see the captain
      again. He was very anxious to be off, and I rather fancy by this time he&rsquo;s
      well out at sea.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, in that case,&rdquo; remarked Stranleigh indifferently, &ldquo;I shall be
      consoled by the assurance that his steamer is uninjured.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      In due time the motor boat returned, and its occupants entered the yacht
      without being seen by their master&rsquo;s guest. The motor boat was hoisted on
      board, and the captain, coming aft, said:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Any further orders, sir?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes. Plymouth, if you please. And, captain, just stop on your way at the
      camp, which I am informed is on the left-hand bank of the river. Draw up
      at the landing if there is one; if not, perhaps Mr. Frowningshield&rsquo;s
      launch will be waiting for him. There are some packages to go ashore.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The steamer proceeded down the river with just enough speed on to give her
      steering way. Frowningshield sat very silent, but his host made up with
      loquacity for the other&rsquo;s taciturnity. He told entertaining stories, and
      related odd experiences, and all with a delicate courtesy, as if his guest
      was the most honored of men, instead of being merely an adventurer and a
      marauder on a gold quest.
    </p>
    <p>
      The captain drew up expertly at the landing. Nothing was to be seen of the
      <i>Rajah</i> that so lately had been berthed there. In spite of the fact
      that they saw their boss stepping ashore, large groups of men had ceased
      work, and were standing twenty or thirty yards back from the landing,
      viewing with eyes of wonderment the trim white steamer that had come out
      of the wilderness. Frowning-shield stepped ashore like a man in a dream,
      and a couple of stewards placed the cases of champagne and the boxes of
      cigars on the rock beside him. Lord Stranleigh leaned against the rail,
      and bade farewell to the manager.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wouldn&rsquo;t you like to come on to Plymouth with us?&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Penny all
      the way. County Council express boat. No stop between Chelsea and London
      Bridge.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;God knows I wish I could,&rdquo; said Frowning-shield, with a deep sigh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, at least,&rdquo; cried Stranleigh cheerfully, &ldquo;we&rsquo;ve had one pleasant
      afternoon, and I&rsquo;m more than grateful for your company. I hope that you
      will find valuable minerals on this spot; a second Klondike or Kimberley
      in either gold or diamonds. Somehow I think you&rsquo;ll be successful, and so
      I&rsquo;ll leave you my best wishes. Good-by, good-by.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The steamer was moving off down the river as Stranleigh waved his hand at
      the choice gang of ruffians that manned the highest outcrop of the reef.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;After all,&rdquo; he murmured to himself, &ldquo;they&rsquo;re Englishmen, poor devils, and
      we&rsquo;re all a long way from home!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The manager standing there on the rock suddenly bethought himself, and
      raised his hat. A cheer broke forth from the outlaws, and they waved aloft
      tattered caps.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pull the whistle, captain, with a hip-hip-hip-hurrah,&rdquo; and the siren
      sounded across the delta.
    </p>
    <p>
      The manager stood for a long while watching the retreating boat, with his
      hands clasped behind him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By God,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know what to make of that man! I believe the
      captain&rsquo;s right, and that he&rsquo;ll capture the <i>Rajah</i> before nightfall,
      yet he&rsquo;ll have no shot from my cannon.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <i>The Woman in White</i>, as soon as she was out of sight of the camp,
      made record time to the coast, traversed the deep channel between the
      river and the sea with some caution, then struck straight out to the west.
      The sun was still about two hours above the western ocean. Far to the
      north the <i>Rajah</i> could be seen keeping closer inshore than seemed
      quite safe, the captain&rsquo;s idea being doubtless to get out of sight behind
      the first headland he might encounter. The heavily laden boat was burning
      up coal with reckless prodigality, the slight wind from the shore carrying
      out to sea a great black banner of smoke. Stranleigh walked forward to the
      captain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Can you overtake him before sunset?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I think so, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I imagine our best plan is to convince him as speedily as possible
      that he can&rsquo;t run away from us. I don&rsquo;t like to see him wasting coal like
      that. Coal is more valuable than the ore he carries until we reach
      Teneriffe. Full speed ahead, captain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The hum of the turbines rose and rose, and the trembling of the yacht
      perceptibly increased as the sharp prow clove through the waters with the
      speed of a torpedo-boat destroyer. The steward, setting out cups and
      saucers for tea, on a wicker table, found some difficulty in keeping the
      jingling dishes from catastrophe. The <i>Rajah</i> had about four hours
      the start, and had probably worried away thirty knots of the long route
      she was to travel. Higher and higher she seemed to rise in the water, and
      the sun was still a good quarter of an hour above the horizon when <i>The
      Woman in White</i> came tearing up alongside to landward of her, carried
      now by her own momentum, for the turbines had been stopped some distance
      away. Apparently everybody on board was leaning over the rail watching the
      amazing speed of the swanlike craft, white and graceful, as she gradually
      slowed down. Stranleigh recognized the anxious face of the captain, and
      shouted up at him:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Tell your stokers to economize on that coal.&rdquo; The captain replied
      truculently:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No one gives orders on this steamer but me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Quite right,&rdquo; replied Stranleigh, with less imperiousness than had barbed
      his first shout. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s why I&rsquo;m asking you to give the command.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain, after a moment&rsquo;s hesitation, sent the order below, then
      turned again to the white vessel, which was now keeping exact time with
      his own black one.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Captain,&rdquo; said Stranleigh, in his ordinary tone of voice, &ldquo;both
      Frowningshield and myself were very sorry you could not lunch with us, so
      perhaps you will be good enough to come aboard this yacht and dine with
      me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A captain cannot leave his ship,&rdquo; curtly replied the master of the <i>Rajah</i>.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ordinarily, no, but this is an exceptional case. I&rsquo;ve got a letter for
      you, captain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then why didn&rsquo;t you give it to me at noon?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, come now, a man can&rsquo;t think of everything when he is overjoyed at
      receiving an expected and very welcome guest. You must admit, captain,
      that once I undertook the work of ocean postman, I lost no time in giving
      you the double knock. I don&rsquo;t think there&rsquo;s anything in these waters would
      have overhauled you so quickly as I have done. Won&rsquo;t you then make an
      exception, and honor us with your presence?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, I will not. If, as you say, you&rsquo;ve got a letter for me, I&rsquo;ll throw
      down a line for it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, on the face of it, that seems fair. A man in England drops you a
      line, and you drop a line for his line. Nevertheless, this letter,
      although addressed to you, I do not intend to part with. There are several
      documents in my pocket which I&rsquo;d like to show you, and I wish to make some
      explanations that will interest you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Look here, Mr. Stranleigh, I&rsquo;m captain aboard this steamer, and I&rsquo;m on
      the high seas. I warn you, before witnesses here, that any interference on
      your part is piracy. I shall not come aboard your steamer, nor shall I
      allow any one from your steamer to come aboard of me. I take orders from
      none but my own masters, the owners of this ship. I am now under their
      orders, and acting upon them. I won&rsquo;t stand any interference.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Again I say quite right, captain. Your sentiments are admirable, and your
      views of nautical duty are correct. Nevertheless, it is necessary that you
      and I should enjoy a quiet talk together, and I ask you to favor me by
      coming aboard.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I won&rsquo;t.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then, as the mountain wouldn&rsquo;t come to Mahomet, Mahomet went to the
      mountain. I ask your permission to go aboard your vessel.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shan&rsquo;t give it. I&rsquo;ve told you that before. Now, sheer off, or I&rsquo;ll put
      a cannon ball into your engine room.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, have you got a cannon ball on board? How jolly! We are entirely
      unarmed so far as ordnance is concerned, but I&rsquo;d like to say, captain,
      that the chances are ten to one your cannon ball wouldn&rsquo;t do much harm.
      You might even plant a floating mine in front of <i>The Woman in White</i>,
      and although it probably would blow her prow up, yet I think, crablike, I
      could crawl backward to the nearest port, as the White Star liner <i>Suevic</i>
      made her way from the Lizard to Southampton.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you going to sheer off, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, and you are not going to fire, either, captain. It isn&rsquo;t etiquette at
      sea to shoot cannon balls at a man until you have finished the cigars he
      has presented to you. I dislike very much to allude to my own gifts in
      this way, but still I wish you to understand that I am well versed in
      nautical law.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I want to get along with my voyage, Mr. Stranleigh, unmolested.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, bless your tarry heart, captain, get along with your voyage. If you
      can run away from us, don&rsquo;t let me put any obstacle in your path.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you sheer off, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly not. I&rsquo;m quite within my rights. This part of the ocean belongs
      as much to me as to the <i>Rajah</i>. I&rsquo;m not delaying you in the least,
      and all your talk of interference is mere humbug. If I ran my craft close
      enough to endanger yours, you might have a right to object; but I call
      your attention to the fact that we are under perfect control, and I can
      keep the distance between the ships to an inch. If I went farther away, I
      should be unable to converse with you without straining my throat, which I
      decline to do. Now, you will neither come aboard my vessel, nor allow me
      to go aboard yours.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s right.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I don&rsquo;t think it is. Nevertheless, you force me to do what I should
      much rather, for your sake, not do, and that is I am compelled to read
      your letter, and the documents I have referred to, in the hearing of your
      crew and my own.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You may read what you like to the crew.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Captain, I ask you to reconsider that dictum. I grant that you might
      honestly have made such a remark on any other voyage you have ever taken
      during your long seafaring life, except this one. Just think for a moment.
      Don&rsquo;t reply rashly, and be assured that I mean no harm to you, nor to
      anybody else aboard your ship. Quite the contrary. What I intend to do
      will be greatly to your advantage, and to that of every man who is with
      you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      When Lord Stranleigh made reference to his present voyage, the captain,
      who had been leaning against the rail, stood up suddenly. The men were
      whispering with one another. The captain saw that Stranleigh had taken
      from his pocket several envelopes, and stood there awaiting his reply. At
      last the captain said huskily:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you come aboard alone, sir?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, quite alone, of course, since it is your wish, or you can come aboard
      here with half a dozen or a dozen men as your bodyguard, if you like.
      Bring the cannon, too, if it makes you feel any safer.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;d rather you came aboard here, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very good. Fling over a slightly stronger line than you&rsquo;d have sent down
      for the letter, and I&rsquo;ll be with you in a jiffy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But how am I to know some others won&rsquo;t climb up?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, hang it, arm your men with handspikes, and knock &rsquo;em down
      again. Don&rsquo;t keep me waiting here all night. It will be dark very soon,
      and I shan&rsquo;t occupy more than ten minutes of your time. You seem spoiling
      for a fight, but I can&rsquo;t accommodate you. I&rsquo;m a man of peace, and that&rsquo;s
      why I shudder when you speak to me of cannon. I swear I&rsquo;ll tell Sir Henry
      Campbell-Bannerman and President Roosevelt the way you&rsquo;re behaving. You&rsquo;re
      a positive danger on the high seas, with your ultimatums, and your shots
      through the engine room, and all that. Heave over a line, and get your men
      to watch that the yacht doesn&rsquo;t spring aboard of you. No wonder we English
      are disliked for our browbeating.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain seemed rather ashamed of his fears in face of this bantering,
      and besides, some of his crew had laughed, which still further
      disconcerted him. A rope fell coiling through the air, and came slap on
      deck.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hang tight aloft there,&rdquo; cried Stranleigh, as he jerked the rope taut,
      swung himself free of his own boat, and clambered up the black cliff of
      the <i>Rajah</i> hand over hand, feet against the side like a monkey.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0007" id="link2HCH0007"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER VII&mdash;THE CAPTAIN OF THE &ldquo;RAJAH&rdquo; STRIKES OIL
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>HE captain strode
      gloomily to the evil-smelling den he called the cabin, and Stranleigh went
      down the steps with him, seating himself at the table.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now, captain,&rdquo; he began, &ldquo;can we be overheard?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I come here as your friend. I want to save you, if possible.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Save me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need any saving.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, you do, and a good deal of it. I thought at first that
      Frowningshield was the sole culprit, and that you were merely an innocent
      victim. I learned to-day that such was not the case; in fact, I surmised
      it before, because when you assisted in planting those mines across the
      Paramakaboo River you must have known you were committing a capital
      offense.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then it wasn&rsquo;t an accident; you <i>did</i> send down the logs?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Of course I did.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You watched us ever since we arrived there?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I came from England for that purpose. I left a week after you did,
      and was there a week before you, more or less. My man, Mackeller, whom you
      kidnapped on board this steamer at Southampton&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t kidnap him, sir. It was Frowning-shield.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I know all about it. Mackeller is on my boat now, within three
      hundred yards of where you are sitting. He was up on the hilltop with a
      telescope, scrutinizing every action of yours since you landed.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But I&rsquo;m compelled to obey orders.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, no, you aren&rsquo;t. If you are ordered to do a criminal action, you must
      not only refuse, but you are in honor bound to give information to the
      authorities.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I had nothing to do with putting Mackeller into the hold. Frowningshield
      put him in, and I didn&rsquo;t know he was there till we were more than a day
      out. It was me insisted he should be sent ashore with the pilot.
      Frowningshield wanted to take him with us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s neither here nor there, captain. Of course, whenever you knew a
      man had been kidnapped in that way aboard your ship, you should have
      turned, made straight back to Southampton, giving information to the
      authorities. But even if such an unlawful action did not arouse your
      suspicions you must have known perfectly well when you planted those mines
      that it wasn&rsquo;t toy balloons you were putting in the water. It&rsquo;s too late
      to pretend innocence. You&rsquo;ve been bribed to commit a crime.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The floating mines weren&rsquo;t set in English waters.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear sir, your offense is against international law. No man is allowed
      to place floating mines in a river up which a British steamer may ascend,
      and so far as that is concerned, you deliberately put them there to wreck
      a British steamer. You are at this moment commanding a pirate ship filled
      with stolen ore.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know nothing about that, sir. This ship was chartered, and I was told
      by my owners to obey the orders of them that chartered her, and that&rsquo;s old
      Schwartzbrod and his gang.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We&rsquo;re merely losing time, captain. You talk about charters and owners.
      Well, I am the owner of the <i>Rajah</i>. I bought her from Sparling &amp;
      Bilge.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So <i>you</i> say. That&rsquo;s nothing to do with me. Even if you bought the
      ship, you are bound by law to carry out the charter. Till a charter runs
      out and isn&rsquo;t renewed, owners are helpless. I obey the charter while it
      holds, and as long as I do that I&rsquo;m doing nothing wrong.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are perfectly well aware of what you are doing. I am convinced of
      that. You were not born yesterday. Now, you are not sailing toward
      Portugal, you are sailing toward a policeman, and it is from that
      policeman I wish to save you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, yes, you&rsquo;d like to get possession of the ship and cargo for yourself,
      wouldn&rsquo;t you?&rdquo; sneered the captain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, exactly.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, you won&rsquo;t get it!&rdquo; cried the master angrily, bringing his huge fist
      down on the table. &ldquo;Talk to me of thieving! What are you? Why, you&rsquo;re a
      pirate, that&rsquo;s what you are. I said so to Frowningshield, and he wouldn&rsquo;t
      believe me. He thought you wouldn&rsquo;t dare come aboard of me on the high
      seas; that you knew better. You and your policeman! Why, damn it all, I&rsquo;d
      be justified in hanging you from the yardarm!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You couldn&rsquo;t do that, captain,&rdquo; protested Stranleigh, with great
      mildness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why couldn&rsquo;t I?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Because those two masts of yours are not provided with yardarms. You
      might possibly hang me from the funnel, or allow me to dangle in chains
      from one of the arms of your steam crane, but that&rsquo;s all.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why don&rsquo;t you and your gang of ruffians climb aboard here like real
      pirates, and make me walk the plank?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have climbed aboard like a real pirate, and I am going to make you walk
      the plank.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The devil you are!&rdquo; cried the captain, rising, his two clenched hands
      resting on the table, his naturally florid face still further flushed with
      wrath. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll show you&mdash;I&rsquo;ll show you what we do to men of your kind
      that dare to come aboard a ship on the high seas.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sit down, my dear man, sit down,&rdquo; pleaded Stranleigh soothingly. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t
      bluster. What&rsquo;s the use of making a fuss? Let&rsquo;s discuss the thing
      amicably.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Make me walk the plank, will you?&rdquo; roared the captain, a-quiver with
      resentment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, well, well, if you object, of course that puts a different complexion
      on the matter. I thought that walking the plank was a customary nautical
      amusement. I seem to have been misled by friend Clark Russell. If it isn&rsquo;t
      etiquette, let&rsquo;s say no more about it. Do sit down, captain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      But the captain wouldn&rsquo;t sit down. His eyes glared, his face grew redder,
      and his lips quivered with animosity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You come alongside with your toy yacht!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a toy, captain, that spins along a little faster than this old tub.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You and your jackanapes dressed up like naval officers, dare to come
      aboard o&rsquo; me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s splendid, captain. I like that phrase, &lsquo;aboard o&rsquo; me.&rsquo; I&rsquo;m
      delighted to have Clark Russell corroborated from your mouth. Yes, I come
      aboard o&rsquo; you. What then?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What then? Why, then you try to browbeat me in my own cabin, on my own
      ship. Who the devil do you think you are, I&rsquo;d like to know?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am Earl Stranleigh of Wychwood.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain now, without being told, slowly relapsed into his chair, and
      gazed across the table at the young man. That latent respect for the
      aristocracy which permeates even the most democratic of his Britannic
      Majesty&rsquo;s subjects caused an instant collapse of the truculence which had
      threatened an abrupt conclusion to the conference. Curiously enough, the
      honest captain never thought of questioning the statement, which had been
      made in a quiet, but very convincing tone.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Earl Stranleigh!&rdquo; he gasped.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes; of Wychwood. We always insist on the Wychwood, though I&rsquo;m sure I
      don&rsquo;t know why, for there isn&rsquo;t another Lord Stranleigh, and Wychwood is
      far from being the most important of my estates. Still, there you have it,
      captain. English life is full of incongruities.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The <i>rich</i> Lord Stranleigh?&rdquo; questioned the captain, with an accent
      on the adjective.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve just told you there&rsquo;s only one.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then why in the name of Neptune are you pirating on the high seas? Is <i>that</i>
      the way you made your money?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, my money was more or less honestly accumulated by my ancestors, but I
      think their method was highway robbery rather than piracy. The looting of
      land that didn&rsquo;t belong to them seemed to occupy their spare time, and so,
      what with the rise of manufacturing cities in the midlands, on portions of
      our property, the discovery of coal mines, and what not, my family
      prospered better than it deserved, and here am I the twentieth-century
      representative of it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If that is so, why the deuce are you meddling in this affair?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Because I like to see a man minding his own business. The ship which you
      so worthily sail is mine. I bought her a few days after you left
      Southampton. Here is the deed of transfer, and here is the letter I spoke
      of, written to you by Messrs. Sparling &amp; Bilge, informing you that I
      am the new owner, that I shall be responsible for your pay hereafter, and
      as a consequence they will be much obliged, as, indeed, so shall I, if you
      do what I tell you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain read the documents with slow care, then looked up.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s Sparling &amp; Bilge&rsquo;s signature all right, and nobody knows it
      better than I do, but what about the cargo? Do you intend to unship at
      Lisbon?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, I intend to run it to Plymouth.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But even if the ship&rsquo;s yours, the cargo isn&rsquo;t.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Surely you knew they were stealing the ore, captain?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They told me they had a right to it for three months. Mr. Schwartzbrod
      showed me papers to that effect. That&rsquo;s why they were in such a hurry.
      Wanted to get as much out in the time as they could, and offered me a
      bonus of five thousand pounds over and above my wages if I ran three
      voyages to Lisbon, and two thousand for each extra voyage within the
      time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then, captain, why didn&rsquo;t they concentrate their energies on the mining
      of the ore, and not bother with the mining of the river?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, Frowningshield told me that they were on the lookout for some
      pirates that was going to interfere with them. We didn&rsquo;t intend to blow up
      any vessels unless they were determined to come up the river in spite of
      us. That&rsquo;s why we didn&rsquo;t put the mines at the mouth of the river. On the
      high ground west of the camp, Frowning-shield had two men on watch all the
      time. If they saw any ship approach, they were to go down the river in a
      boat that was kept below the mines, and order the steamer to go back. If
      the captain wouldn&rsquo;t go back, then he came on at his own risk.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I see. And did Frowningshield tell his men to inform captain and crew
      that the river was mined?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now, captain, talking as one seafaring man to another, didn&rsquo;t all this,
      in conjunction with the large sums of money promised you, strike you as
      rather fishy? Did this appear to you an honest trading?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, earl, I&rsquo;ve sailed to all parts of distant seas, and I&rsquo;ve known
      things done that would have looked mighty queer in Southampton Harbor, and
      yet they were all right as far as ever I knew. Things happen in the South
      Seas that would seem rather odd in Bristol Channel, you know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You didn&rsquo;t think you were running any risk, then?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, risk! A seafaring man runs risks every time lie leaves port. If this
      was a risk, there was good money at the end of it, and that isn&rsquo;t always
      the case when a man ships on a tramp steamer nowadays, what with
      everything cut to pieces by foreign competition. You see, earl, men born
      to money don&rsquo;t always appreciate what people will do who&rsquo;re trying to pile
      up a little cash against their old age. I&rsquo;ve got a wife and family in a
      hired house in Southampton&mdash;three girls I&rsquo;ve got at home, earl, and
      girls is helpless left poor&mdash;not to mention my old woman.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain&rsquo;s eyes took on a dreamy, far-away look that seemed to
      penetrate and question the future. He had, for the moment, forgotten the
      young man sitting opposite him, and went on as if talking to himself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s a piece of land running down to Southampton water&mdash;five
      acres and a bit more. Somebody built a cottage there and put up a flagpole
      on the lawn in front. Then they got tired of it, and it&rsquo;s for sale. A
      thousand pounds they want for the place, everything included. There&rsquo;s a
      few trees, and there&rsquo;s outhouses; splendid spot to raise chickens. Then
      there&rsquo;s a veranda in front, and an oldish man might sit in an easy-chair
      smoking his pipe, and see the American liners come sailing past. And my
      family&rsquo;s living in a rented house on a back street. I&rsquo;ve always wanted
      that bit of land, earl, but never had the money to spare, and when I come
      to settle down, like as not somebody else will own it, and we couldn&rsquo;t
      afford it, anyhow. Risks? Of course there&rsquo;s risks, but when I think of
      that little cottage&mdash;well, I took the risk, earl.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear captain,&rdquo; said the earl softly, &ldquo;your bit of land makes me
      ashamed of myself, and of my moral lectures. I have so much land, and
      others have so little. Here&rsquo;s a hard-working man like you, landless, and
      here&rsquo;s a loafer like me with thousands of acres! Hang me if I wouldn&rsquo;t
      turn Radical were it not for the awful example of William Thomas Stead.
      Well, captain, that plot of land is yours from this moment. If somebody
      else has bought it in your absence, we&rsquo;ll evict them. I&rsquo;ll go bail that
      old Schwartzbrod will pay you all he promised whether you make the voyages
      or not. Indeed, you are not going to make the voyages, as a matter of
      fact. I don&rsquo;t believe Schwartzbrod ever intended to keep his promise, and
      I very much doubt if you could collect. Now, I&rsquo;m an excellent collector,
      and I think I can persuade Schwartzbrod to plead for the privilege of
      paying you. You see these city men are much too sharp for simple, honest
      chaps like you and me. After you had done their work, they would have left
      you in the lurch if you were caught, or cheated you out of your
      compensation if you escaped. You may depend upon it, Schwartzbrod and his
      crowd have done everything in the most legal manner. Indeed, as a matter
      of fact, the last time I saw him he wheedled a document from me which I
      have reason to believe covers the villainy of this expedition. I do not in
      the least doubt that if I took the case into the law courts I&rsquo;d get
      beaten. That&rsquo;s why I preferred to fight the case on the high seas, where
      an injunction can&rsquo;t be served till it&rsquo;s too late. You and I, captain, are
      not shrewd enough to be a match for these rascals.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was almost a smirk of self-satisfaction on the captain&rsquo;s face as he
      found himself thus linked with a man of Lord Stranleigh&rsquo;s rank.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, earl,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;what do you want me to do?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They were interrupted by the heavy steps of the mate coming down the
      stairs.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you want?&rdquo; roared the captain. &ldquo;Get out of here.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Beg pardon, sir,&rdquo; explained the mate, &ldquo;but they&rsquo;re getting uneasy on the
      yacht, and want to know what&rsquo;s become of the boss.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Just excuse me for a moment, captain,&rdquo; said Stranleigh, &ldquo;and I&rsquo;ll speak
      to them. You know you did rather tyrannize over us when we first hailed
      you, and they probably think you&rsquo;ve Mac-kellered me. I rather flatter
      myself I&rsquo;ve made a pun there, for &lsquo;keller&rsquo; is the German for cellar.&rdquo; The
      young man sprang lightly up the steps, and went over to the bulwarks.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is it all right, sir?&rdquo; shouted Mackeller.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;All right, thank you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s getting dark, you know. Hadn&rsquo;t I better heave a revolver up to you,
      and if they try any tricks you can fire it off, and we&rsquo;ll be aboard before
      you can say &lsquo;Schwartzbrod.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, Mackeller, Mackeller, you&rsquo;re always thinking of deadly weapons and
      acts of piracy! No wonder I get a bad name in marine circles. Everything&rsquo;s
      going smoothly, and I expect to be with you within ten minutes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Stranleigh returned to the cabin, where he found the captain sitting,
      staring into vacancy. Some one had lit an odorous oil lamp.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, captain, before answering your question, I wish to say that I am
      interested in mercantile traffic aside from my ownership of the <i>Rajah</i>.
      Before I left England I reserved for you the berth of captain on a new
      steamer called the <i>Wychwood</i>, twice the size of this boat, that is
      intended for the South American trade. I think she will be ready for you
      by the time we reach Plymouth, and the moment we are in Plymouth I shall
      hand you a check for a thousand pounds to secure that bit of land by
      Southampton water. What sort of a crew have you aboard here? A mutinous
      lot, or easy going?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, the crew&rsquo;s all right, earl. They&rsquo;re Devon men, most of them. It was a
      rough lot of passengers we took out under charge of Frowning-shield, but
      they herded most by themselves, and held no truck with the crew. The
      crew&rsquo;s all right, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you think any of the crew knew what was going on?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, I don&rsquo;t suppose anybody knew what was going on but me and
      Frowningshield.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Would you like to have your present crew with you on the new steamer?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir, I would.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Officers, too?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I would. Officers, too.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very well, I want you to come aboard my yacht, and be captain of her from
      here to Plymouth. Take the mate with you, if you like, or any of the other
      officers, and take such of the crew as are not Devon men. I&rsquo;ll put some of
      my own fellows aboard in their place.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You mean me to leave the ship, my lord?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes. The yacht&rsquo;s captain and mate will take the place of you and your
      mate.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain&rsquo;s face was a study of indecision and doubt.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It doesn&rsquo;t seem quite right, my lord.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your late owners have told you to obey me, and I am your new owner. It is
      quite right. I have merely transferred you to the yacht as if I were
      transferring you to a ferry boat, in order to take you the more quickly to
      your new command. We&rsquo;ll reach Plymouth in a fortnight, or three weeks
      before the <i>Rajah</i> does. I&rsquo;d rather you didn&rsquo;t go to Southampton, but
      if you think you can keep out of sight, I don&rsquo;t mind your running across
      there, seeing your family, and securing that property. Indeed, if the
      property is still in the market, and the house empty, there&rsquo;s no reason
      why you shouldn&rsquo;t move your people into it. You&rsquo;ll have time enough, then
      you can return to Plymouth, see to your new ship, and engage what men you
      need to supplement the <i>Rajah&rsquo;s</i> crew when she arrives.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain made no reply: bowed head and wrinkled brow showed that a
      mental conflict was going on.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose you are very well known in Southampton?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; he said; &ldquo;not so well known as you might think. I&rsquo;m there for a
      little while, then off on a long voyage. Not as well known as might be.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You see, captain, I&rsquo;m determined to get out of old Schwartzbrod the money
      wherewith to pay not only you, but Frowningshield and his men. I don&rsquo;t
      intend to leave them marooned there while Schwartzbrod sits safe in
      London, so I wish no rumor of what has taken place to reach the ears of
      Schwartzbrod and his syndicate, therefore I don&rsquo;t want you to be seen and
      recognized by anybody, if possible, and if you are recognized I am anxious
      that you should not talk about what has occurred.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I see. You want to get all the witnesses shipped off to South America.
      Well, you know, my lord, meaning no disrespect, your way of doing things
      seems a little fishy, too, as you said a while ago.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Of course it looks fishy, but you must fight a whale with a shark if you
      haven&rsquo;t got a harpoon. I must either go to law, which is the harpoon, with
      old Schwartzbrod, who is the whale, or else adopt his own methods, and
      play the shark. You&rsquo;ve got to choose which course of fish you&rsquo;re going to
      take, and you&rsquo;ve got to give your order to the waiter now.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Suppose I refuse, what will you do? Attempt to capture us?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Bless you, no. I&rsquo;ll merely follow you, just as a shark follows a doomed
      vessel. The moment you approach a port that contains a British consul,
      I&rsquo;ll dash on ahead, show my papers, and set the law in motion, which, as I
      have informed you, I am reluctant to do. The moment that happens I can&rsquo;t
      save you, captain. I don&rsquo;t know what the penalty is, or whether there is a
      penalty. Perhaps your obedience to orders may allow you to slip through
      the meshes of the net, and then again perhaps it won&rsquo;t. If it doesn&rsquo;t,
      then that little cottage on Southampton water, which was yours a moment
      ago, will never be occupied by your family. Oh, hang it all, I&rsquo;m either
      coercing or bribing you now, whichever it is. You must make a free choice.
      Whatever happens, I&rsquo;ll buy that piece of land, and present it to your
      wife, if you will tell me where it is, and give me her address. Now,
      captain, make your choice: the whale or the shark.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The captain heaved a deep, almost a heartrending sigh, that seemed to come
      from the very bottom of his hoots. He rose slowly and ponderously, and
      stretched forth his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lord Stranleigh,&rdquo; he said solemnly, as one about to cross the Rubicon,
      &ldquo;Lord Stranleigh, I am ready to walk the plank.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      When Lord Stranleigh emerged from the captain&rsquo;s cabin of the <i>Rajah</i>,
      and drew a long, satisfying breath of the sweet evening air outside, he
      saw that the moon had risen, while the glow from the sunset still tinted
      the western sky. The slight breeze from Africa had completely died away,
      and the sea lay around the two ships smooth as a polished mirror. At a
      word from Stranleigh the captain of the yacht drew her alongside the
      Rajah, and the engines of both steamers stopped. Captain Wilkie,
      forewarned, had all his belongings packed, and they were speedily swung
      aboard the black steamer. The captain of the Rajah, and his mate, flung
      their possessions into boxes, and thus the transfer was made without loss
      of time.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mackeller,&rdquo; said Stranleigh, &ldquo;I fear that luxury is thrown away on you,
      and besides, experience on the yacht has shown you that there is little
      chance of anything exciting happening. It must discourage you to remember
      that none of your repeating rifles have even been unpacked, so I will
      cause the cases to be swung aboard the <i>Rajah</i>, with sufficient
      ammunition to massacre our entire naval force, and I&rsquo;ll give you six of my
      gamekeepers. You can either use the gamekeepers to shoot the crew, or arm
      the crew and eliminate the gamekeepers. I had intended to take the crew of
      the <i>Rajah</i> upon the yacht, and put the crew of the yacht on the <i>Rajah</i>,
      but I am so selfish that I cannot bring myself to trust those clumsy
      seafarers from a tramp steamer with the somewhat delicate organization of
      my yacht. Will you accept the commission, and sail for home on the
      comfortless <i>Rajah?</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall be delighted, sir,&rdquo; said Mackeller. &ldquo;You see, I feel just a
      little uncertain about the wisdom of leaving Captain Wilkie unprotected
      with what is, after all, a strange crew. Their captain gives them a good
      character, but Captain Wilkie, who is a martinet in his way, may get at
      loggerheads with them, so it is well that he should have a bloodthirsty
      commander and irresistible force at his beck and call. But remember,
      Peter, that for every sailor you shoot, one of your gamekeepers must take
      to the sailoring trade, which might turn out inconvenient in a storm, so
      repress your war spirit until the captain orders it to belch forth. I
      imagine your frowning appearance as, resembling the German Emperor, you
      walk the deck, will quell any incipient mutiny in the bud, if buds are
      quelled. Nevertheless, it is safer to hold the rifles in the background in
      case of an emergency. So call for six volunteers from among my men, and
      then fling your trunk aboard the lugger, after which it will be good-by
      till I meet you again at Plymouth.&rdquo; When the exchange was completed the
      white yacht drew away from the tramp and speedily disappeared to the north
      like a ghost. Captain Wilkie watched her departure with regret, and was
      unhappy at his promotion to the unkempt and dirty tramp steamer, with her
      slouching crew, dressed like scarecrows. The new commander of the yacht
      felt equally out of place in this trim, scrupulously clean, nickel-plated,
      bride&rsquo;s-cake of a ship, while the sailors, in their spick-and-span natty
      uniforms, gave him the impression of being in a nightmare where an uncouth
      private had been placed in charge of a company of officers. As he was
      about the same size as Wilkie, the useful Ponderby, at Stranleigh&rsquo;s
      orders, fitted him out next morning in a gorgeous uniform which added to
      the beauty of his outward appearance without materially augmenting his
      inward comfort. However, the bluff captain understood his business, no
      matter what costume he wore, and Stranleigh, studying him very
      unobtrusively as the voyage went on, came to place a great confidence in
      him, and felt rather ashamed of the distrust that had caused him to
      transfer the captain from the <i>Rajah</i> to the yacht. Before a week was
      past, he was certain that this gruff sea dog would have taken the <i>Rajah</i>
      direct to Plymouth once he had given his word, quite as faithfully as
      Captain Wilkie was doing. Although Stranleigh said nothing of this trust,
      and even doubted if the simple old man had seen the reason of the change,
      he nevertheless resolved to make amends, though not in words. The weather
      throughout had been almost obtrusively gentle, and Stranleigh complained
      that the voyage was falsifying all of Clark Russell&rsquo;s novels. He grumbled
      to the doctor that his faith in Clark Russell was undergoing a tremendous
      strain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When we reach a dead calm in one of Clark Russell&rsquo;s novels,&rdquo; he said to
      the doctor, &ldquo;we always know what to expect. Suddenly out of the west comes
      a ripping cyclone which lays us over on our beam ends. Then wild, blinding
      rain and utter darkness, lit up only by vivid flashes of lightning. Every
      one has to cling to whatever is nearest him: overboard go the chicken
      coops, and there is such a general pandemonium that the voice of command
      cannot be heard. Crash go the masts, funnels, and what not: we right
      ourselves, staggering under the mountainous waves, and find ourselves a
      dismantled hulk next morning, with the cook missing, and no hot rolls for
      breakfast. Now, in reality we have had evenings without a zephyr afloat,
      then follows a peaceful night, and morning comes with a maidenly blush,
      like that on a new-born rose. I imagine the ocean has improved since Clark
      Russell&rsquo;s time, or perhaps the Government weather bureau has regulated
      tilings. We are a wonderful people, doctor, and at last Britannia really
      does rule the waves.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Fast as his yacht was, the young man had become tired of the voyage. He
      yearned for his morning paper and a stroll down Piccadilly. When well
      across the placid Bay of Biscay, he called up one of his wireless
      telegraphers, and said to him:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I say, my son, cannot you tune up your heavenly harp, and pull us some
      news down out of the sky? Aren&rsquo;t we within the Marconi range of
      civilization yet?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir. Several private messages have come through, and some scraps of
      news, but nothing important. The chancellor of the exchequer is speaking
      in the House of Commons on some bill, so far as I understand it, to
      regulate the Bank of England.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I fear that wouldn&rsquo;t be very exciting reading, my boy, and besides, I
      don&rsquo;t understand finance, and never did. Still, I&rsquo;d welcome even the words
      of a politician this evening, so if the chancellor is still talking, write
      out what he says. And, by the way, if you get a chance to talk back, you
      might ask the horizon what races were on to-day, and which horses won.
      After all, it is encouraging to know that the chancellor of the exchequer
      is on his feet. That shows that old England is still a going concern. It
      seems a year since I was there.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The operator departed for the telegraphic cabin, and Stranleigh went on
      with his cigar and after-dinner coffee. Presently the young man returned
      with a grin on his face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He&rsquo;s at it again, sir,&rdquo; he said, and handed Stranleigh a sheet of paper
      headed:
    </p>
    <h3>
      &ldquo;CHANCELLOR EXCHEQUER.
    </h3>
    <p>
      &ldquo;During the past decade our bank rate has been in a state of constant
      fluctuation, changing many times, and ranging from two-and-a-half to seven
      per cent., a variation which has exercised anything but a beneficial
      effect upon business. The gold in the issue department of the Bank of
      England usually amounts to about thirty millions of pounds, which are
      shown to be inadequate to the needs of our time. On the other hand, the
      Bank of France rarely allows its reserve to fall below a hundred millions
      of pounds, with a consequence that the French bank rate remains steady at
      from two-and-a-half to three per cent., and has not risen to four per cent
      for thirty years. In the twelve months preceding the report of 1904 the
      bank rate of France had not been changed once, while our own bank rate had
      jumped from&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Here Stranleigh crumpled the paper into a ball in his hand, and flung it
      into the ocean.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Great heavens!&rdquo; he cried. &ldquo;I wonder what kind of a brain revels in that
      sort of rot! And not a word about the races! What do these telegraphers
      imagine news is, anyhow?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The ignorant young man little dreamed that the message he was reading
      would exercise an astounding influence on his own career on that day when
      the Bank of England was compelled by the new Act of Parliament to raise
      its reserve of gold from thirty millions of pounds to one hundred
      millions. A world-wide financial disturbance lay ahead which Stranleigh
      did not suspect any more than did the wise lawmakers who passed the bill
      by a large majority. Most of them, including his lordship, thought the
      races more important and interesting.
    </p>
    <p>
      The captain strolled aft. More and more as the days went on the frivolous
      young man&rsquo;s liking for this veteran of the sea had increased, in spite of
      the fact that the captain had endeavored to carry away his gold mine.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sit down, captain,&rdquo; he cried. &ldquo;What will you drink?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A cup of coffee, to keep me awake. I expect to be up all night, or at
      least till we pass the Ushant.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Right you are, and coffee it is. Oh, by the way, I have changed my mind,
      and you must change your course. Instead of striking straight across from
      Ushant to Plymouth, steer your course up the Channel for Southampton.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very good, earl.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And I&rsquo;ve also changed my mind regarding that bit of land of yours.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, have you, earl?&rdquo; said the captain, with a catch in his voice, and
      disappointment visible on his countenance.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, that&rsquo;s the reason we&rsquo;re going to Southampton. You will lay this
      yacht up&mdash;I think that is the nautical term&mdash;alongside your bit
      of land. As you know, I am anxious that you shouldn&rsquo;t be seen, and also
      that nobody aboard should have a chance to talk.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll see to that, earl.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear man, don&rsquo;t call me earl. I told you I was an earl in strict
      confidence. Haven&rsquo;t you noticed that everyone addresses me as &lsquo;sir,&rsquo; and I
      don&rsquo;t even insist on that. We are all free and equal at sea, except the
      captain, who rules over us. When we reach Southampton water I&rsquo;ll go ashore
      in the motor boat, will call on the land agent, secure the estate of five
      acres, give the deeds to your wife, and invite her and the family to come
      up and view the cottage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She knows where it is, sir. We&rsquo;ve often been there together.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then you&rsquo;ll grant no shore leave, not even to yourself. You&rsquo;ll keep the
      lads busy while I&rsquo;m ashore. Take the yacht to the nearest coaling station,
      wherever it is, and fill her up with black diamonds. We may want to go to
      New York, for all I know. What time do you expect to pass Ushant?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;About one bell, sir; half an hour after midnight.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How long is the run from Ushant to Southampton?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We should do it easy in eleven hours.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then we&rsquo;ll reach there at noon to-morrow? Very good. You had better,
      perhaps, run me right up to Southampton, attend to the port formalities,
      see to the coaling, and be lying off your bit of property by six o&rsquo;clock
      next evening. I&rsquo;ll stop the night at a hotel, so you needn&rsquo;t trouble about
      me. How large is your family, captain?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The three eldest are at sea, and the three girls at home with the
      missus.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Three girls? Oh, that&rsquo;s jolly! Very well, I think we&rsquo;ve everything
      arranged. You will see that the motor boat is ready for me at the landing
      both to-morrow afternoon and all next day. I shall probably want to run up
      the bay to the bit of land, or down, whichever it is. I suppose you can
      point it out to me as we pass?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, yes, sir. I never enter or leave Southampton without looking at that
      bit of ground.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very well. At about five o&rsquo;clock p.m. day after to-morrow I shall invite
      the missus and the three girls to take a trip with me in the motor boat.
      Arriving there I shall hand the keys and the deeds to the lady of the
      house, and if you come ashore I&rsquo;ll introduce you to the family. You may
      stop all night ashore. Next morning take the yacht, and navigate her
      slowly round to Plymouth. There you may give everybody shore leave, but
      don&rsquo;t overdo it. You understand what I want, which is that no man shall
      talk about the mine in West Africa or the transfer in midocean, so I
      expect you to keep your section of the crew in hand. I can answer for my
      fellows. Oh, yes, by the way, I&rsquo;ll take my woodmen off at noon to-morrow,
      together with all that are left of my gamekeepers, and send them home,
      including the excellent Ponderby, so you will have none to deal with
      except those belonging to the yacht.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <i>The Woman in White</i> did even better than the captain anticipated,
      and landed her owner in Southampton at ten minutes to eleven. He bade
      farewell to his men, and dispatched them to their homes, none the poorer
      for their long voyage. He visited the land agent&rsquo;s office, transacted his
      business within ten minutes, drew his check, and told the manager to have
      the papers ready by twelve o&rsquo;clock next day. Then he went to the back
      street, and knocked at the number the captain had given him. The door was
      opened by a buxom young woman, in whose flashing eyes he recognized her
      father.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, my dear,&rdquo; he said, chucking her under the chin, &ldquo;are you the
      gallant captain&rsquo;s daughter, as we say in the revised version of
      &lsquo;Pinafore&rsquo;?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl drew back in righteous anger, and if a dagger glance of the eyes
      could have slain, he would have been in danger, but the callous young man
      merely laughed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mother at home?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who are you?&rdquo; demanded the offended girl.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s the same question your father asked me. It&rsquo;s a secret, and I&rsquo;ll
      tell it only to your mother.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      At this moment the mother, hearing the high tones of her daughter, and
      fancying something was wrong, appeared in the hall; a stout, elderly
      woman, who frowned at the tall, nattily dressed stranger.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My name is Stranleigh, madam, and I am by way of being a shipowner. Your
      husband is one of my captains.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is nothing of the sort. He is captain of the <i>Rajah.</i>&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Quite right, and I am the owner of the <i>Rajah</i>. Your husband has
      just bought that little bit of property down the bay; the one with a
      cottage and a flag pole, you know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What are you talking about, sir? My husband is hundreds and hundreds of
      miles away at sea.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, no, madam, it&rsquo;s you who are at sea. Of course, he didn&rsquo;t buy the
      property personally. I have acted as his agent, and I come merely to tell
      you of the transaction. The deeds are promised by noon to-morrow, when I
      am promising myself the pleasure of handing them to you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then his venture has turned out a success? I had my doubts of it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So had I, madam, but we who predict disaster are often confounded.
      Everything is all right, as you remark.&rdquo; Then, turning to the one who had
      let him in, he said reproachfully: &ldquo;Please don&rsquo;t scowl at me like that,
      but close the door and invite me into the parlor. Don&rsquo;t you see I&rsquo;m a
      visitor?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl said nothing, but looked at her mother.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come this way, sir,&rdquo; said the woman, opening the door at the left,
      whereupon the girl, with visible reluctance, closed the front door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where are the other two girls&rsquo;?&rdquo; demanded Stranleigh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They are in the kitchen, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Please send for them. I wish to see the whole family, being so well
      acquainted with the captain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The still unmollified door opener, at a nod from her mother, disappeared,
      returning shortly with the two younger children shrinking bashfully behind
      their elder sister, who quite evidently ruled the household.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah,&rdquo; said Stranleigh, &ldquo;what a fine family! It is evident that these girls
      did not depend for their beauty solely on their father.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I think,&rdquo; said the elder girl haughtily, &ldquo;that my father is the finest
      looking man in the world.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;ll change your mind some of these days, miss, or I&rsquo;m greatly
      mistaken. I admit the worth of your father, but you&rsquo;ll never see his
      picture on a beauty post card. And now, if you&rsquo;re prepared for a bit of
      news, and if every one promises not to faint, I&rsquo;ll tell you what it is.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, he isn&rsquo;t arrested?&rdquo; cried the wife in alarm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Arrested? Of course not. Why should he be? He is coaling my yacht at this
      moment somewhere in Southampton harbor, within half a mile of where you
      are sitting.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There were some shrieks of surprise at this intelligence, but Stranleigh
      went on unheeding.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now, as I have told you, the cottage is yours, and I wish you to do
      something very enterprising; to hustle, as they say in America. My motor
      boat is down at the landing, and can take you to and from the cottage as
      often as you like, and it will be speedier than tram or cab or railway
      carriage. Missus, you will be chief of the finest burst of shopping
      Southampton has ever seen. Your husband will land at the cottage at six
      o&rsquo;clock tomorrow night. The chances are that the empty house will not be
      any the worse for a little cleaning, so your eldest daughter here should
      take with her a host of charwomen, and scrub the edifice from top room to
      basement. Then, madam, you are to go to whatever furniture shop you
      choose, ignore all that you now possess, and furnish every room in that
      house before four o&rsquo;clock tomorrow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But, sir, that will cost a mint of money, and we&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I didn&rsquo;t expect it done for nothing, and I haven&rsquo;t the remotest idea
      what the total will be. But here are three hundred pounds to go on with. I
      got this purposely to-day in crisp Bank of England notes. Whatever more is
      needed I will pay you to-morrow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But how are we ever to pay you, sir?&rdquo; asked the astonished woman.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No need of that, madam. Your husband did me a very great service, and I
      am merely arranging this as a pleasant surprise for him, and also because
      of the intense admiration your eldest daughter exhibits for me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl tossed her head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He&rsquo;s a humbug, mother; don&rsquo;t believe him. There&rsquo;s something bogus in all
      this. I&rsquo;ll warrant you those notes are counterfeit. He wants to get us out
      of the house, and then steal the furniture. I read about a person like him
      in the papers. He got seven years.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lord Stranleigh laughed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, how sharp you are, unbelieving creature. You&rsquo;ve guessed it the first
      time. Is the furniture in this villa worth three hundred pounds?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, it isn&rsquo;t,&rdquo; said the girl promptly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very well. Take those notes to the bank, and get golden sovereigns for
      them, leaving your mother on guard till you return. They&rsquo;ll probably ask
      you where you got them, and you will answer thus: &lsquo;They are the proceeds
      of a draft for three hundred pounds which Lord Stranleigh of Wychwood
      cashed at the London and County to-day, at half-past eleven.&rsquo; If they
      still wish to know how you came by them, say that Lord Stranleigh is the
      owner of several steamships, and that your father is captain of the
      largest of them. Say nothing of the <i>Rajah</i>, because he is now chief
      of a steamer twice her size. I took notes because they were lighter to
      carry, but when you get the gold I hope you will do what I ask of you, and
      leave this house promptly, so that I can steal its furniture without
      molestation.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you Lord Stranleigh?&rdquo; gasped the mother.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, madam, and there&rsquo;s one other favor I beg of you, and of these three
      charming girls. Mention to nobody that your father has returned. Neither
      he nor I wish this known for a while yet, and I am quite sure four women
      can keep the secret, even if one man can&rsquo;t.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s nothing wrong, is there?&rdquo; asked the anxious woman.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing wrong at all. It&rsquo;s merely a matter concerning his new ship, which
      lies at Plymouth, where he must go on the morning of day after tomorrow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Energetic as the captain&rsquo;s family was, they never put in such a day and a
      half of nervous, capable speed in their lives before, and this included
      the intervening night, during which none of them slept.
    </p>
    <p>
      By five o&rsquo;clock in the afternoon everything was ship-shape, although not
      quite to the satisfaction of the eldest daughter, and at six Lord
      Stranleigh had the felicity of introducing the captain to his possessions,
      human and material, old and new. Then he rushed back in his motor boat,
      and took the train to London.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
